<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=22&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;22</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=24&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;24&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_23.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_23.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>KING OF CHRISTMAS</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>2 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
With eight Speccy Christmases to choose from before the market
declined so much that the Spectrum Top Ten games charts stopped being
published in the magazines, which software label do you think was the
King Of Christmas?
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If we take the Christmas Top Tens published in the March issues of
Your Sinclair and give software labels ten point for each Number One,
nine for each Number Two, and so on down to one point for a Number
Ten, then the winner by a mile is Ocean, even when the Imagine games
are separated from them.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d23_1985_ad11.png" target="1985_ad11.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1985_ad11_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=213></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>OK, so they weren't so great in the early days...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Ocean may have won this accolade purely because they published a
higher number of full price games each year compared to their rivals,
helped by the fact that they published games from 1983 until 1992 -
practically the whole of the Spectrum's commercial lifetime - but
their Christmas output is more interesting than that.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d23_1987_ad8.png" target="1987_ad8.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1987_ad8_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=217></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>...but they were warming up at the end of 1987...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Their history can be divided into two halves, with the second half
starting at Christmas 1987. Whilst their output has been mainly
licensed games from the arcades or toys and television shows and
movies, before that Christmas the quality of their games was pretty
poor to say the least. Sure, there were some good games dotted around
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/vG8f95A-pxM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/vG8f95A-pxM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Kenny Everett's 12 Days of Christmas</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Incredibly silly, but very funny! <b><i>(4:20)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vG8f95A-pxM" target="vG8f95A-pxM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

such as <i>Daley Thompson's Decathlon</i>, <i>Cobra</i>, and anything coming from
Jon Ritman, but during that time Ocean was more remembered for late
games based on popular TV shows which were awful when they finally
appeared after a heap of marketing and hype - step forward <i>Knight
Rider</i>, <i>Street Hawk</i>, <i>Miami Vice</i>, <i>It's A Knockout</i>... the list was
embarrassingly long.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The end of 1987 was a watershed moment - the last of the toy licences,
<i>MadBalls</i>, was got out of the way as the Ocean label ditched the TV and
toy licences in favour of getting big name arcade and film licences
whilst bumping up the programming quality of their games. Throughout
1987 and 1988 the magazine ratings earned kept on rising, and from the
end of 1988 over the following couple of years it was very rare for an
Ocean title to not score upwards of 90% when reviewed. The <i>Knight
Rider</i> and <i>Kong</i> days were long gone, Ocean had become the leading
software label and pretty much stayed that way until they started
seriously moving onto the 16-bit machines, leaving their Spectrum
titles as also-rans.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=522 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d23_1988_ad8.png" target="1988_ad8.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1988_ad8_small.jpg" WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d23_1988_ad17.png" target="1988_ad17.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1988_ad17_small.jpg" WIDTH=68 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d23_1989_ad9.png" target="1989_ad9.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1989_ad9_small.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d23_1990_ad4.png" target="1990_ad4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d23_1990_ad4_small.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=100></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=7 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>...and then the coast was clear to slaughter the opposition.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/miosjU1rlYo&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/miosjU1rlYo&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>BBC2 Starts Up On Christmas Day 1988</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Featuring a logo so '80s that it hurts. <i>Nice</i>... <b><i>(2:06)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=miosjU1rlYo" target="miosjU1rlYo">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/tAcEzhQ7oqA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/tAcEzhQ7oqA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>WarGames Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Would you like to play a game? <b><i>(2:18)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tAcEzhQ7oqA" target="tAcEzhQ7oqA">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

This meant that Ocean barely featured in the Christmas charts until
1987, at which point they'd get at least two or three titles into the
Top Ten, and yet the Number One spot always seemed to elude them. It
must have been terribly frustrating for them to get three Christmas
Number Twos in four years, usually getting beaten by a licence which
was slightly bigger than Ocean's best.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For a latecomer like me, whose first proper Speccy Christmas was in
1987, Ocean usually stood out from the crowd, surrounded by the likes
of US Gold (arguably an Ocean spin-off), Imagine (definitely so) and
Activision. I'm so glad that I caught them at their finest, getting
hooked on the hype their games produced over the subsequent years.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;So, if Ocean were the Kings Of Christmas, what was the best Speccy
Christmas ever? Find out tomorrow...
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
